 “movieland,” and their attractions to certain stories and stars. Moreover, many of these weekend pages, daily columns, and film reviews were written and consumed by women, including one teenage girl who compiled a rare surviving set of scrapbooks. Based on extensive original research, Menus for Movieland substantially revises what moviegoing meant in the transition to what we now think of as Hollywood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picturesxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aMotion picturesxMarketingxUnited States. 0aMotion picturesxPress coveragexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aMotion picturesxPress coveragezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxMarketing. 0aNewspapersxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aNewspapersxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096188340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961883423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961883/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles